{"title":"SECOND: Mitigating Perceptual Hallucination in Vision-Language Models via Selective and Contrastive Decoding","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Vision-Language Models often hallucinate objects because current multi-scale designs indiscriminately fuse patches across scales, diluting object-centric evidence, and training new multi-scale encoders is costly.","method":"SECOND introduces a training-free, selective multi-scale integration. It appends down-sampled vision encoders by bilinearly interpolating positional embeddings and resizing inputs, forming 3–4 coarse-to-fine stages. At each stage, it computes a visual attention map by combining vision self-attention with language cross-attention, then uses an entropy-driven dynamic ratio (p_select) to pick the top-attended patches for the next higher-resolution stage, accumulating attentions across scales. This attention-guided, coarse-to-fine patch selection preserves object-relevant density while suppressing irrelevant background patches, reducing hallucinations."},{"problem":"Single-step contrastive decoding in VLMs typically focuses on suppressing language priors and underuses the structured progression of visual evidence across scales, limiting hallucination mitigation.","method":"SECOND proposes multi-stage Contrastive Decoding that treats early (sparse, low-res) stages as amateurs and later (dense, high-res) stages as experts, contrasting their logits across consecutive stage pairs with parameters α, β, and γ. By leveraging the staged evolution of visual detail introduced via selective patch integration, this decoding amplifies distinctions between sparse and dense visual information. It consistently improves over patch selection alone and over single-stage CD on object perception benchmarks (e.g., POPE) and shows advantages on broader evaluations (e.g., MMStar)."},{"problem":"There is no formal bridge between a VLM’s visual focus and its hallucination likelihood, leaving multi-scale design choices under-motivated.","method":"SECOND introduces a diagnostic/theoretical framework: define hallucination probability P_Hal from generation likelihood and propose the Attention Dice Coefficient that aligns combined vision self-attention and language cross-attention with object masks. Empirically, lower Dice correlates with higher P_Hal; Theorem 3.2 shows smaller patches (higher resolution) increase the Attention Dice when attention aligns with objects. Theorem 3.3 proves multi-stage patch selection monotonically lower-bounds/increases the Attention Dice across stages, justifying SECOND’s selective multi-scale design."}]}
